HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 329
BY REPRESENTATIVE WALTERS
COMMENDATIONS: Commemorates the one hundred sixth anniversary of the Harlem
Renaissance
1 A RESOLUTION
2 To commemorate the one hundred sixth anniversary of the Harlem Renaissance.
3 WHEREAS, the Harlem Renaissance emerged after World War I as the Great
4 Migration brought an array of African American artists and scholars to the Harlem
5 neighborhood in New York City; the cultural explosion was widespread and occurred in
6 Cleveland, Los Angeles, and other cities impacted by the migration; and
7 WHEREAS, the Harlem Renaissance is among the most significant eras of cultural
8 expression in American history, encompassing poetry and prose, painting and sculpture, jazz
9 and swing, and opera and dance, and the movement united these diverse art forms by
10 emphasizing their realistic presentations of what it meant to be Black in America; and
11 WHEREAS, Zora Neale Hurston was an anthropologist, folklorist, and prolific writer
12 who cared deeply about African American people and culture and broke literary norms by
13 focusing her work on the experience of Black women; she is often referred to as the "Queen
14 of the Harlem Renaissance" for her impact and contributions during the era; she co-founded
15 the nation's oldest Black collegiate newspaper, The Hilltop, during her time as a student at
16 Howard University; she also established the school of dramatic arts at Bethune-Cookman
17 College in 1934; she is considered among the greatest writers of the twentieth century, and
18 her work continues to influence writers throughout the world; and
19 WHEREAS, Alain Locke was a Harvard-educated writer, critic, and teacher who has
20 been referred to as the "dean" of the Harlem Renaissance; he described the cultural
