1 movement as a "spiritual coming of age" in which African Americans transformed "social
2 disillusionment to race pride"; and
3 WHEREAS, Langston Hughes described the movement's diverse art as an
4 "expression of our individual dark-skinned selves," and he identified a new militancy in
5 African Americans' assertion of their civil and political rights; and
6 WHEREAS, the Harlem Renaissance's most significant contributors were
7 intellectuals, W.E.B. Du Bois, Marcus Garvey, Cyril Briggs, and Walter Francis White;
8 performers, Josephine Baker and Paul Robeson; writers and poets, Zora Neale Hurston, Effie
9 Lee Newsome, and Countee Cullen; visual artists, Aaron Douglas and Augusta Savage; and
10 an extraordinary list of legendary musicians, including Louis Armstrong, Count Basie, Eubie
11 Blake, Cab Calloway, Duke Ellington, Billie Holiday, Ivie Anderson, Fats Waller, Jelly Roll
12 Morton, and many others; and
13 WHEREAS, Harlem became a central location of American culture at the height of
14 the movement; the neighborhood was a bustling hub of African American-owned and run
15 publishing houses and newspapers, music companies, playhouses, nightclubs, and cabarets;
16 the movement's literature, music, and fashion defined "cool" for all Americans, regardless
17 of race, and its influence spread across the globe; and
18 WHEREAS, the Harlem Renaissance brought notice to the great works of African
19 American art and inspired future generations of artists and intellectuals; the movement
20 shared a portrait of African American life, identity, and culture with the world and radically
21 redefined how people of other races viewed and understood African Americans and their
22 experience; and
23 WHEREAS, the Harlem Renaissance provided African Americans with a new spirit
24 of self-determination and pride, a new social consciousness, and a new commitment to
25 political activism, all of which served as the foundations for the civil rights movement of the
26 1950s and 1960s.
27 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
28 Legislature of Louisiana does hereby commemorate the one hundred sixth anniversary of the
29 Harlem Renaissance and does hereby recognize the outstanding contributions made by
30 African Americans to the cultural identity of the United States.
